{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Enforce release-source authorization + version lockstep before publication\n\nRe-anchor the release to the proven OSS pattern (uv model): a single\n`workflow_dispatch`-from-`main` workflow that asserts version-lockstep + ancestry,\nthen **builds and publishes directly** via PyPA Trusted Publishing (OIDC — no\nlong-lived secret, no tag relay), gated on a required-reviewers `pypi` environment\nre-keyed from \"v* tags only\" to \"`main` via dispatch\". The source is reviewed-and-\nlanded `main` **by construction**. (Readiness Finding 1 — verified VALID against\n`release.yml:17-21`, `infra/terraform-github/main.tf:23-101`, `docs/releasing.md`.)\n\n## Why\n\n`main` is constrained to the Gerrit replication deploy key, but `refs/tags/v*` was\ndeliberately left open (`infra/terraform-github/main.tf:23-28`) so a human can push\na `v*` tag to drive PyPI + MCP-registry + GitHub-Release publication\n(`release.yml:17-21`, jobs `build`/`publish`/`github_release`/`mcp_registry`). The\nonly gate anywhere is `if: github.event_name == 'push' && startsWith(github.ref,\n'refs/tags/v')` (release.yml:53/81/116) — nothing checks that the tagged SHA is an\nancestor of (or equal to) reviewed `main`, verifies any Gerrit/CI result for that\nexact SHA, or asserts version consistency. A PEP 740\nattestation would correctly name this repo's workflow but cannot distinguish a tag\non reviewed `main` from a tag on any other commit. Separately, the three version\nvalues (`pyproject.toml:10`, `server.json` top-level and `packages[].version`) are\nkept in lockstep only by a manual runbook (`docs/releasing.md`), so a future\nmismatch would publish disagreeing versions across the PyPI / GitHub-Release / MCP\nchannels with no machine check.\n\n## What\n\nAdopt uv's proven release process and pydantic's pre-build version check, in this\norder of control strength:\n\n- **Primary control — initiate from `main` via `workflow_dispatch` (source reviewed\n  by construction).** Make `workflow_dispatch` the sanctioned release trigger, run\n  from the `main` ref. Because the GitHub mirror's `main` is exactly the\n  Gerrit-reviewed-and-landed history, releasing from `main` guarantees the source is\n  reviewed **by construction** — the same guarantee the wider OSS world gets from\n  \"release only from the protected branch.\" This replaces \"accept whatever commit an\n  arbitrary pushed tag points at,\" which was the actual divergence from consensus.\n- **Version-lockstep, before build (pydantic pattern).** A first job parses the\n  intended version and every manifest and asserts exact equality **before build**:\n  `version_input == project.version == server.json.version ==\n  each server.json.packages[].version`; mismatch fails before build.\n- **Ancestry assertion (belt-and-suspenders).** In the same dispatch job, assert the\n  checked-out `main` HEAD is reachable from `origin/main` via\n  `git merge-base --is-ancestor \"$GITHUB_SHA\" origin/main` (checkout with\n  `fetch-depth: 0` + `git fetch origin main`, since a shallow clone defeats ancestry —\n  the repo documents this at `reconcile-bridge.yml:83-88` and `verify-identity.yaml`\n  already uses `fetch-depth: 0`). With dispatch-from-`main` this is redundant with the\n  ref guard, kept as defense-in-depth.\n- **Build, then publish DIRECTLY via PyPA Trusted Publishing — no tag relay.** The\n  same workflow builds and then publishes using OIDC (`id-token: write`, the existing\n  `pypa/gh-action-pypi-publish` trusted-publishing flow). There is **no** intermediate\n  tag push: a tag pushed by the built-in `GITHUB_TOKEN` would not trigger a downstream\n  workflow anyway (GitHub's anti-recursion rule), so a two-phase relay is avoided\n  entirely, and no PAT / GitHub App secret is introduced.\n- **Compose with — do not regress — F3 and F4 (this story lands last).** Per the\n  dependency chain (F4 → F3 → F1), this story edits `release.yml` on top of F4's and\n  F3's changes. The dispatch trigger must **retain** F3's build-once → test-wheel /\n  test-sdist → hash-gated-`publish` job graph and F4's `mcp_verify`/`mcp_registry`\n  split + evidence-consolidation job — the trigger change swaps only *how the run\n  starts and is authorized*, not the internal job structure. Concretely, **re-key\n  every downstream version source and job guard from `github.ref_name` / the\n  tag-context `if:` to the `workflow_dispatch` input** (the `github_release` and\n  `mcp_registry` jobs derive their version from the input, and their\n  `if: github.event_name == 'push' && startsWith(github.ref, 'refs/tags/v')` guards —\n  which go always-false once the tag trigger is removed — are updated to the dispatch\n  condition).\n- **Human authorization — re-key the `pypi` environment + a fail-closed preflight\n  (uv release-gate + PyPA Trusted Publishing).** The `publish` job runs in the `pypi`\n  deployment environment with **required reviewers**, so publication needs a second\n  human's approval. Because the job now runs in the dispatch (`refs/heads/main`)\n  context rather than a tag context, the environment's deployment-ref policy is\n  **re-keyed from \"v* tags only\" to \"`main` via `workflow_dispatch`\"** with required\n  reviewers — **no new secret**. This is the single most security-critical gate\n  (anyone with `actions:write` can start a dispatch; only the environment's reviewers +\n  branch policy enforce \"a second human approves each publish\"), so it must not live\n  as an un-versioned console setting that could be silently cleared. Rather than couple\n  to the AWS-authed `terraform-drift.yml` (a different provider/auth model), enforce it\n  **at release time**: a **preflight step queries the GitHub REST API\n  (`GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/environments/pypi`) and FAILS the release closed** if the\n  environment lacks required reviewers or its deployment-branch policy is not\n  `main`-only. This detects drift exactly when it matters (it blocks the actual\n  publish, stronger than a periodic plan), is codebase-verifiable (the step exists in\n  `release.yml`), and needs only the workflow's own read token. Net effect: \"only `v*`\n  tags may publish\" becomes the stronger, self-enforced \"only a dispatch-from-`main`,\n  reviewer-approved run may publish — and a release aborts if that protection is\n  missing\".\n- **Tag + GitHub Release created AFTER a successful publish (record only).** Once\n  publish succeeds, the workflow creates the `v*` tag and the GitHub Release for the\n  record/mirror; the tag is an **output**, never a trigger. The MCP job derives the\n  version from the dispatch input (not from a tag).\n- **No raw-tag publish path.** With the environment keyed to dispatch-from-`main`, a\n  hand-pushed `v*` tag cannot reach the `pypi` environment and therefore cannot\n  publish — this eliminates the \"arbitrary pushed tag publishes\" surface that was the\n  original finding, rather than merely gating it.\n- **Verify the guard LOGIC with unit tests (no live staging needed).** Extract the\n  three guards into small testable units — the version-lockstep comparison, the\n  ancestry check, and the env-preflight response parsing — and unit-test them with\n  fixtures (matching/mismatching versions; ancestor/non-ancestor SHAs; env-protection\n  present/absent JSON). This makes the negative paths codebase-verifiable without any\n  live publish. The guard *steps existing* in `release.yml` is likewise\n  codebase-verifiable.\n- **Guard-firing is verified AUTONOMOUSLY on the real workflow — no staging fork.** The\n  three abort guards precede every publishing job, so they can be demonstrated to fire\n  WITHOUT any real publish: after this story lands, the agent triggers `release.yml` via\n  `gh workflow run` with a non-`main` ref and a mismatched version input, and confirms via\n  `gh run view --log` that each run aborts at its guard step before build/publish. This\n  needs only the environment's `workflow` scope (present) and produces no PyPI/registry\n  side effect. A staging fork + a TestPyPI trusted-publisher would only be needed to\n  exercise the *positive* real-publish path, which is deliberately NOT part of verifying\n  this story (publishing a real release is not a story deliverable); that positive path is\n  covered by the unit-tested guard helpers + the codebase-verifiable dispatch-from-`main`\n  wiring. **Live `pypi` environment config is also autonomous:** the agent reads and, if\n  drifted, configures the environment's required reviewers + `main`-only branch policy via\n  the admin GitHub API (the environment holds a `repo`-scoped admin token), then confirms\n  — escalating to request access only if the API write is denied.\n- **`main.tf` / tag-push restriction stays OUT of scope (unchanged, deliberate).**\n  `main.tf:23-28` documents the `tag_lock` was removed (no viable GitHub tag bypass\n  actor in this mirror topology) and the contract test\n  `tests/unit/test_mirror_lock_terraform.py::test_module_is_main_only_no_tag_lock`\n  codifies \"no tag lock\". We do not restrict *who* can push a tag; publication safety\n  now comes entirely from dispatch-from-`main` + the re-keyed reviewer-gated environment.\n- Record the approved SHA, version, manifest versions, and artifact hashes in release\n  evidence.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `.github/workflows/release.yml` — switch the trigger to `workflow_dispatch` (version\n  input, run from `main`); enforce `github.ref == 'refs/heads/main'`; add the\n  version-lockstep + ancestry checks before build; build then publish directly via the\n  OIDC trusted-publishing flow gated on the re-keyed `pypi` environment; create the\n  `v*` tag + GitHub Release after a successful publish (record only). Remove the\n  `push: tags: v*` publish trigger (it can no longer reach the re-keyed environment).\n- **Autonomous post-landing verification (no operator fork):** after this story lands,\n  the agent (a) triggers `release.yml` via `gh workflow run` with invalid inputs and\n  confirms via `gh run view` that each guard aborts before publish (needs only the\n  `workflow` scope), and (b) reads/configures/verifies the live `pypi` environment's\n  required reviewers + `main`-only branch policy via the admin GitHub API (`repo` scope).\n  Both record their evidence as comments on this ticket. No staging fork or TestPyPI\n  publisher is required; escalation is a fallback only if the needed GitHub scope is\n  denied.\n- Unit tests for the extracted guard helpers (version-lockstep, ancestry, env-preflight\n  parsing) — the codebase-verifiable proof the guards behave correctly.\n- `.github/workflows/release.yml` — a **preflight step** in the dispatch flow that\n  calls `GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/environments/pypi` and fails the release if the\n  environment lacks required reviewers or a `main`-only deployment-branch policy\n  (fail-closed drift detection at release time). No `infra/terraform-github/`,\n  `terraform-drift.yml`, or terraform-contract-test changes (the GitHub provider's\n  AWS-vs-GitHub auth split made drift-workflow coupling disproportionate; the\n  preflight is the stronger, self-contained control). `infra/terraform-github/main.tf`\n  and its no-tag-lock contract test remain **unchanged**.\n- `docs/releasing.md` — document the dispatch-from-`main` process, the version-lockstep\n  invariant, and the required environment reviewers. **Section ownership:** this story\n  owns the \"Release-source authorization\" section **and rewrites the now-obsolete\n  existing sections it invalidates** — the \"Tag → PyPI publishes automatically\"\n  procedure (replaced by dispatch-from-`main`) and the \"Hard rules\" manual-lockstep\n  framing (now machine-enforced). (Finding 3 owns \"Build-once\" + rewriting the\n  \"Post-release smoke test\" section; Finding 4 owns \"Pinning\" — so the three concurrent\n  release stories do not overlap-edit the same headings.)\n- Out of scope: the build-once / pinning work (Findings 3 and 4 — separate stories\n  that also touch `release.yml`; coordinate ordering per the epic).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] **AC 0 (dependency gate — verify before starting).** This story composes on top of\n  F3 (build-once) and F4 (pinning), which land first per the epic chain (F4 → F3 → F1).\n  Before implementation, confirm by grep that `release.yml` on the working base already\n  contains F3's `test-wheel` / `test-sdist` jobs and its hash-gated `publish` (no rebuild),\n  AND F4's `mcp_verify` / `mcp_registry` split + the evidence-consolidation job. If they are\n  absent (F3/F4 not yet landed/merged into this branch's base), STOP and rebase onto the\n  landed F3/F4 first — this story only re-keys *how the run starts and is authorized* and must\n  not re-introduce or fork those job graphs. (This makes the cross-story dependency an\n  explicit, checkable precondition rather than an assumed baseline.)\n- [ ] The workflow **retains** F3's build-once → test-wheel/test-sdist → hash-gated `publish`\n  job graph and F4's `mcp_verify`/`mcp_registry` split + evidence-consolidation job unchanged\n  in structure (verified by grep: those job names still present after this story's trigger\n  re-key), so the authorization change is additive, not a rewrite.\n- [ ] `release.yml` is triggered by `workflow_dispatch` (version input), contains a\n  guard step failing when `github.ref != 'refs/heads/main'`, a version-lockstep step,\n  and an ancestry step (`git merge-base --is-ancestor`, checkout `fetch-depth: 0` +\n  `git fetch origin main`), all before build; and it has **no** `push: tags` publish\n  trigger — all codebase-verifiable from the workflow definition.\n- [ ] The workflow **retains** F3's build-once → test-wheel/test-sdist →\n  hash-gated-`publish` job graph and F4's `mcp_verify`/`mcp_registry` split +\n  evidence-consolidation job, and re-keys the `github_release`/`mcp_registry` version\n  sources + guards from the tag context to the `workflow_dispatch` input — verified by\n  the workflow definition still containing those jobs and no `github.ref_name`/tag-`if:`\n  version derivation remaining.\n- [ ] The workflow publishes directly via the OIDC trusted-publishing flow (no\n  intermediate tag push / no relay / no PAT) and creates the `v*` tag + GitHub Release\n  only **after** a successful publish (tag is an output, not a trigger) — codebase-\n  verifiable from the job graph.\n- [ ] A release-time preflight step calls `GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/environments/pypi`\n  and fails the release closed when required reviewers are absent or the\n  deployment-branch policy is not `main`-only — codebase-verifiable (the step exists in\n  `release.yml`); the actual live environment configuration is set + verified\n  **autonomously** via the admin GitHub API (see the environment-config AC below). So a\n  cleared environment protection aborts the release instead of silently enabling\n  single-actor publishing.\n- [ ] Unit tests for the extracted guard helpers pass: version-lockstep flags a\n  deliberate mismatch, the ancestry check rejects a non-ancestor SHA (and accepts a\n  non-tip ancestor), and the env-preflight parser fails on env-protection-absent JSON —\n  all codebase-verifiable without a live publish.\n- [ ] The guards are demonstrated to **fire in a real `workflow_dispatch` run**,\n  completed **autonomously** by the agent (no operator fork/TestPyPI needed): after this\n  story lands, the agent triggers `release.yml` on `navapbc/rebar` via `gh workflow run`\n  with (i) a **non-`main` ref** and (ii) a **mismatched version input**, and confirms via\n  `gh run view --log` that each run **ABORTS at its guard step before any\n  build/publish/tag job** — so NO PyPI / MCP-registry / GitHub-Release side effect occurs\n  (the ref guard, version-lockstep, and ancestry checks all precede every publishing job).\n  The run URLs + the aborting guard-step log lines are recorded as a comment on this\n  ticket. The **positive** clean-dispatch → real-PyPI publish is deliberately NOT\n  triggered (publishing a real release is out of scope for verifying the story; the\n  guard-PASS path is covered by the unit-tested helpers + the codebase-verifiable\n  dispatch-from-`main` wiring). Escalate only if `gh workflow run` / `actions:write` is\n  unavailable in the environment.\n- [ ] The live `pypi` GitHub environment is **configured to the codified policy —\n  required reviewers enabled AND a `main`-only deployment-branch policy — and verified,\n  autonomously** by the agent using the environment's admin GitHub token: it reads\n  `GET /repos/navapbc/rebar/environments/pypi`; if required reviewers are absent or the\n  branch policy is not `main`-only, it **configures** the environment via\n  `PUT /repos/navapbc/rebar/environments/pypi` (`reviewers` set to at least the repo\n  owner / a designated maintainer; `deployment_branch_policy` = custom + a `main`-only\n  branch policy via the deployment-branch-policies endpoint), then **re-reads to confirm**\n  compliance. The before/after API responses are recorded as a comment on this ticket,\n  and the release-time preflight (the AC above) then passes against the live environment.\n  Escalate only if the admin API write is denied (request repo-admin on `navapbc/rebar`).\n- [ ] `docs/releasing.md` documents the dispatch-from-`main` process, the\n  version-lockstep invariant, the environment re-key, and the reviewer requirement.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass, and the change lands via the\n  Gerrit two-vote gate.\n\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784157198612852001,"uuid":"b30f05a3-0f5d-4ac6-a70a-0614725428b0"}